al Competence of Planners -- t14. Negotiating Culture: Towards Greater Competency in Planning -- t15. Educating Planners for a Cosmopolitan Society: A Selective Case Study of Historically Black Colleges and Universities -- t16. Moving the Diversity Agenda Forward0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDemographic change and a growing sensitivity to the diversity of urban communities have increasingly led planners to recognize the necessity of planning for diversity. Edited by Michael A. Burayidi, Cities and the Politics of Difference offers a guide for making diversity a cornerstone of planning practice.The essays in this collection cover the practical and theoretical issues that surround this transformation, discussing ways of planning for inclusive and multicultural cities, enhancing the cultural competence of planners, and expanding the boundaries of planning for multiculturalism to include dimensions of diversity other than ethnicity and religion – including sexual and gender minorities and Indigenous communities. The advice of the contributors on how planners should integrate considerations of diversity in all its forms and guises into practice and theory will be valuable to scholars and practitioners at all levels of government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningxPolitical aspects. 0aCity planningxSocial aspects. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aMulticulturalism. 0aSocial integration. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAgrawal, Sandeep K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurayidi, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurayidi, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoan,